Class Set

  • java.lang.Object
    • chh.math.sets.Set
  • Direct Known Subclasses:
    EmptySet, Pair, Powerset, Subset, Union

    public abstract class Set
extends java.lang.Object
    A set is that which may contain elements; these elements, in turn, are also sets.

      • includes

        public abstract boolean includes(Set x)
        Returns whether this Set has the specified Set as a subset. The set x is a subset of a set y exactly when "all the elements of x are in y", that is: for all sets t, if t is an element of x then t is an element of y. Although there is a Subset class, some Set objects may have the property of being a subset of this one without being an instance of the Subset class.
        Parameters:
        x - the specified set
        Returns:
        true if this set contains all the elements of x
        See Also:
        Subset

      • equals

        public boolean equals(Set x)
        Returns whether the specified Set has the same elements as this Set. Two sets x and y are equal (have the same elements) exactly when they include each other: for all sets t, t is an element of x if and only if t is an element of y. If x is empty, and this set is empty, they are equal.
        Parameters:
        x - the specified set
        Returns:
        true if x and this set are both empty, or this set and x include each other
        See Also:
        includes(Set)

      • isEmpty

        public abstract boolean isEmpty()
        Returns whether this Set has no elements. A set y is empty exactly when: for all sets t, t is not an element of y. Although there is a EmptySet class, some Set objects may have the property of being empty without being an instance of the EmptySet class.
        Returns:
        true if this set has no elements
        See Also:
        EmptySet
